## 3. Core Concepts

### 3.1 BEGINNER

#### 3.1.1 Variables

```bash
name="Alice"            # no spaces around =
count=5
echo "$name has $count items"     # always quote expansions

readonly PI=3.14        # constant
unset count             # remove a variable

# Command substitution
today=$(date +%F)
files=$(ls | wc -l)
```

> **Always quote variables** (`"$var"`) to prevent word-splitting and globbing bugs.

#### 3.1.2 Special variables

| Variable | Meaning |
|----------|---------|
| `$0` | Script name |
| `$1`, `$2`, ... | Positional arguments |
| `$#` | Number of arguments |
| `$@` | All arguments (as separate words, quoted) |
| `$*` | All arguments (as one word) |
| `$?` | Exit status of last command |
| `$$` | Current process PID |
| `$!` | PID of last background command |

#### 3.1.3 Input and output

```bash
echo "Standard output"
printf "%s is %d years old\n" "Alice" 30    # printf: precise formatting

read -p "Enter your name: " username        # read input
read -s -p "Password: " pass; echo          # silent (no echo)
```

#### 3.1.4 Conditionals

```bash
if [[ $count -gt 10 ]]; then
  echo "many"
elif [[ $count -eq 0 ]]; then
  echo "none"
else
  echo "few"
fi

# String and file tests
[[ -z "$var" ]]     # true if empty
[[ -n "$var" ]]     # true if non-empty
[[ "$a" == "$b" ]]  # string equality
[[ -f file ]]       # regular file exists
[[ -d dir ]]        # directory exists
[[ -e path ]]       # exists
[[ -r/-w/-x path ]] # readable/writable/executable
```

> Prefer `[[ ]]` (Bash) over `[ ]` (POSIX test) â€” safer with strings and supports `&&`, `||`, `=~`.

#### 3.1.5 Numeric comparisons and arithmetic

```bash
[[ $a -lt $b ]]       # -lt -le -gt -ge -eq -ne
(( a < b ))           # arithmetic context
result=$(( a + b * 2 ))
(( count++ ))
```

> Bash does **integer** math only. For floating point use `bc` or `awk`.

#### 3.1.6 Loops

```bash
for i in 1 2 3; do echo "$i"; done
for f in *.txt; do echo "$f"; done
for i in {1..5}; do echo "$i"; done           # brace expansion
for ((i=0; i<5; i++)); do echo "$i"; done      # C-style

while read -r line; do echo "$line"; done < file.txt

until [[ $x -ge 3 ]]; do echo "$x"; ((x++)); done
```

### 3.2 INTERMEDIATE

#### 3.2.1 Functions

```bash
greet() {
  local name="$1"          # local scope
  echo "Hello, $name"
  return 0                 # exit status (0-255)
}

greet "Bob"

# Capture output
result=$(greet "Carol")
```

> Use `local` for variables inside functions to avoid clobbering globals. Functions "return" data via `echo`/stdout, not `return` (which is a status code).

#### 3.2.2 Arrays

```bash
fruits=("apple" "banana" "cherry")
echo "${fruits[0]}"          # apple
echo "${fruits[@]}"          # all elements
echo "${#fruits[@]}"         # length (3)
fruits+=("date")             # append
for f in "${fruits[@]}"; do echo "$f"; done

# Associative arrays (Bash 4+)
declare -A ages
ages[alice]=30
ages[bob]=25
echo "${ages[alice]}"
for k in "${!ages[@]}"; do echo "$k = ${ages[$k]}"; done
```

#### 3.2.3 String manipulation

```bash
s="Hello, World"
echo "${#s}"                 # length
echo "${s:7}"                # substring from index 7 â†’ "World"
echo "${s:0:5}"              # "Hello"
echo "${s/World/Bash}"       # replace first â†’ "Hello, Bash"
echo "${s//o/0}"             # replace all o â†’ "Hell0, W0rld"
echo "${s,,}"                # lowercase
echo "${s^^}"                # uppercase

file="/path/to/archive.tar.gz"
echo "${file##*/}"           # basename â†’ archive.tar.gz
echo "${file%/*}"            # dirname â†’ /path/to
echo "${file%.*}"            # strip last ext â†’ archive.tar
echo "${file##*.}"           # last ext â†’ gz

# Default / required values
echo "${VAR:-default}"       # use default if unset/empty
echo "${VAR:?must be set}"   # error & exit if unset
```

#### 3.2.4 Exit codes and conditional chaining

```bash
command && echo "succeeded"      # runs if exit 0
command || echo "failed"         # runs if non-zero
command || exit 1                # bail out on failure

mkdir -p /tmp/x && cd /tmp/x      # chain dependent steps
```

#### 3.2.5 Case statements

```bash
case "$1" in
  start)   echo "starting" ;;
  stop)    echo "stopping" ;;
  restart) echo "restarting" ;;
  *)       echo "usage: $0 {start|stop|restart}"; exit 1 ;;
esac
```

#### 3.2.6 Redirection and pipes

```bash
command > out.txt            # stdout to file (overwrite)
command >> out.txt           # append
command 2> err.txt           # stderr to file
command > out.txt 2>&1       # both to file
command &> all.txt           # both (Bash shortcut)
command < input.txt          # stdin from file
cmd1 | cmd2 | cmd3           # pipe stdout â†’ stdin

echo "log line" >&2          # write to stderr

# Here-document / here-string
cat <<EOF
multi-line
text with $variable expansion
EOF
grep "x" <<< "$mystring"     # here-string
```

#### 3.2.7 Reading arguments and getopts

```bash
while getopts "f:v" opt; do
  case "$opt" in
    f) file="$OPTARG" ;;
    v) verbose=1 ;;
    *) echo "usage: $0 [-v] -f file"; exit 1 ;;
  esac
done
shift $((OPTIND - 1))
```

### 3.3 ADVANCED

#### 3.3.1 Strict mode (safer scripts)

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail
IFS=$'\n\t'
```

- `set -e` â€” exit immediately on any command failure.
- `set -u` â€” error on use of unset variables.
- `set -o pipefail` â€” a pipeline fails if **any** stage fails (not just the last).
- Restricting `IFS` avoids word-splitting surprises.

This **"unofficial strict mode"** catches a huge class of bugs and is recommended for production scripts.

#### 3.3.2 Traps and cleanup

```bash
tmpdir=$(mktemp -d)
cleanup() { rm -rf "$tmpdir"; }
trap cleanup EXIT             # always clean up on exit
trap 'echo "Interrupted"; exit 130' INT TERM
```

`trap` runs a handler on signals/events (EXIT, ERR, INT, TERM) â€” essential for cleaning up temp files and graceful shutdown.

#### 3.3.3 Error handling patterns

```bash
die() { echo "ERROR: $*" >&2; exit 1; }

command -v jq >/dev/null || die "jq is required"
[[ -f "$config" ]] || die "config not found: $config"

# Run with explicit checks even under set -e
if ! output=$(some_command 2>&1); then
  die "some_command failed: $output"
fi
```

#### 3.3.4 Process substitution and advanced redirection

```bash
diff <(sort a.txt) <(sort b.txt)        # treat command output as files
while read -r l; do echo "$l"; done < <(grep x file)   # avoid subshell var loss
```

> Piping into `while` runs it in a subshell (variables don't persist). Use process substitution `< <(...)` to keep variables.

#### 3.3.5 Parameter expansion mastery

```bash
${var:-default}     # default if unset/empty
${var:=default}     # assign default if unset
${var:?error msg}   # fail if unset
${var:+alt}         # use alt if set
${var#pattern}      # remove shortest leading match
${var##pattern}     # remove longest leading match
${var%pattern}      # remove shortest trailing match
${var%%pattern}     # remove longest trailing match
${var/find/replace} # replace first
${var//find/replace}# replace all
${!var}             # indirect expansion
${var:offset:len}   # substring
```

#### 3.3.6 Working with text tools

Bash shines when combined with classic tools:

```bash
grep -E "error|fail" log.txt          # search
sed 's/old/new/g' file                # stream edit
awk '{ sum += $1 } END { print sum }' # field processing/math
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd               # extract fields
sort | uniq -c | sort -rn             # count and rank
tr 'a-z' 'A-Z'                        # translate
xargs -n1 -P4 command                 # parallelize
find . -name "*.log" -mtime +7 -delete
jq '.items[].name' data.json          # parse JSON (external tool)
```

#### 3.3.7 Debugging

```bash
bash -x script.sh         # trace each command as executed
set -x; ...; set +x       # trace a section
bash -n script.sh         # syntax check without running
PS4='+ ${BASH_SOURCE}:${LINENO}: '    # richer trace prefix
```

Always run **`shellcheck`** â€” it catches quoting, unset-variable, and portability bugs before runtime.

#### 3.3.8 Robust script template

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail
IFS=$'\n\t'

readonly SCRIPT_DIR="$(cd "$(dirname "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}")" && pwd)"
log()  { printf '[%s] %s\n' "$(date +%T)" "$*"; }
die()  { printf 'ERROR: %s\n' "$*" >&2; exit 1; }

usage() { echo "Usage: $0 [-v] <arg>"; exit 1; }

main() {
  local verbose=0
  while getopts "v" opt; do
    case "$opt" in
      v) verbose=1 ;;
      *) usage ;;
    esac
  done
  shift $((OPTIND - 1))
  [[ $# -ge 1 ]] || usage

  local tmp; tmp=$(mktemp)
  trap 'rm -f "$tmp"' EXIT

  log "Processing $1"
  # ... work ...
}

main "$@"
```

